				\begin{document}$$\Lambda  = const\,\cdot\,{\eta ^{ - 1}}.$$\end{document}
However, the slope of the line in the Walden plot is slightly below one, expected for ideal behavior.17 This can be related to the clustering of ions or to how ionic the liquid actually is—the iconicity of the liquid.18 There are some examples where ILs are found above the ideal Walden line.16 These are usually protic ILs, where a mobile proton can contribute with a hopping mechanism to the conductivity in excess of the viscous flow (see the article by Yasuda and Watanabe in this issue).

As for other liquids, the temperature dependence of the inverse of the viscosity, η −1, of ILs is well described by the empirical Vogel-Fulcher-Tamman (VFT) equation:
(2)η−1=η0−1exp(BT0T−T0)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
