				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma  = {\sigma _0}\exp \left( {{{B{T_0}} \over {T - {T_0}}}} \right)$$\end{document}
where σ0 in this case is the high temperature limit of the ionic conductivity. Thus, to obtain high conductivity, a low glass transition temperature is desired.22,23 Figure 4 shows the temperature dependence of the ionic conductivity for a few selected ILs.24,25 The deviation from Arrhenius behavior is quite obvious, and when comparing it with the glass transition temperature, it is clear that the magnitude of the ionic conductivity at a fixed temperature correlates well with Tg. This is even more obvious when the same data are plotted with a Tg -scaled temperature axis (Figure 4b). All conductivity curves now collapse onto a master curve as long as the material is in the liquid state.24,25
